This is a fried sticky rice ball from Vietnam, and it's one of the coolest street foods I've ever seen. It's made by adding some soft sticky rice into hot oil and then breaking the sticky rice up into a bunch of small pieces, where it's then mixed around for several minutes. Eventually, it's shaped back together into a ball and pressed to make sure everything's holding together. And then all of a sudden, almost like magic, it begins to bubble and then puffs all the way up into a perfect ball. My mom thinks my daughter is too boyish. I have an eight-year-old daughter who just started at a new school. She's doing great, except for one big problem: my super involved family. My mom and older sister love being part of the school. They volunteer for everything, like bake sales and helping out during lunch. But they've always had strong opinions about how I raise my daughter, and now that they're involved in her school, it's gotten worse. At first it was small stuff, like swapping out her snacks because they thought fruit roll-ups weren't healthy. That was annoying, but not a big deal. Then they started showing up at recess, making her play with kids she didn't like so she could make more friends. One time, my mom made her hand out homemade motivational cards to every kid in her class. My daughter was so embarrassed. The worst part? They pulled her out of gym class without telling me because they thought dodgeball was too rough for girls. Instead, they signed her up for a knitting club. My daughter was upset and crying because she loves dodgeball, but my mom told her it was unladylike. I'd had enough. I went to the principal and asked for a rule that my family can't interfere with anything at school without my permission. The principal agreed, and now they can't change my daughter's activities, lunch, or anything else. Now my mom and sister are calling me bad parents

What was the moment you realized you had to call the police? I was 20, doing Uber part-time while at university. One evening, I decided to take one last ride. It was 10 minutes away from where I lived, so I accepted it. The account name was under Charlotte. When I arrived, a guy who looked to be in his 50s got in. I asked, for Charlotte? He said, yes, that's my wife who booked it for me. He mentioned he was going on a date with a girl he had been talking to for a few weeks, and this was the first time she said yes. I was confused because he just said his wife booked the ride for him, but I was tired, so I let it slide. After a 15-minute drive, I dropped him off at a house where a girl who looked like a minor was waiting for him. I was confused, but I acted as if I was waiting for another ride. I stayed and watched, realizing he was meeting up with a minor. Guilt and fear hit me because she looked to be about the same age as my sister. The girl appeared uncomfortable, and he was visibly forcing her to go inside the house. My heart raced. I drove off and called the police. I was shaking, terrified because I know he doesn't have good intentions. When the police arrived, they found the girl crying and arrested the man. It turned out he and his wife had been involved in similar incidents before. They both got arrested, and I was relieved that I called the police.

My mom wished that I would disappear from her life, so I gave her exactly what she wanted, and now she's miserable. My mother weaponized disappointment like other parents used praise. She'd sigh when introducing me to friends, hang up on me mid-sentence if I wasn't saying something impressive enough, and her house was filled with photos of my perfect cousin Sarah who she always compared me to. Even her compliments came wrapped in poison. You look pretty today, which is rare. She started early. When I brought home a report card with straight A's and one B plus, she drove to school and demanded they remove me from honors classes because obviously I couldn't handle the pressure. The month after that, I won second place at the science fair, and she told the winner's mother, loud enough for everyone to hear, that my daughter probably cheated and still couldn't win. How disappointing. When I got into my dream college, she called admissions and tried to decline my acceptance because state school would be more appropriate for someone of your abilities. She didn't even leave my boyfriend out of it, announcing at family dinner that he was doing charity work by dating down. When I bought my first house, she posted on Facebook that I'd finally found a place that matches my low standards, with photos highlighting every flaw. If I even confronted her about any of this, she'd call other relatives immediately. I'm worried about her mental health. She keeps imagining I said terrible things when all I've ever done is support her. Maybe she needs some professional help. The breaking point came last winter when my appendix burst and I was rushed into emergency surgery. I called my mother while terrified and in pain, begging her to come give me some assurance. She sighed at my voice and said, I won't come. Do you even realize how disappointed I am that my only child can't even stay healthy? Sarah's mother never has to deal with hospital visits. She hung up before I could respond. While nurses prepped me for surgery, I checked Facebook one last time. My mom had posted 10 minutes after our call. Some days I wish I could just start over with a child who doesn't constantly disappoint me. It's like I might as well not have one at all. My own friends were texting me screenshots, horrified that my mother would write this while I was being wheeled into surgery. That's when something inside me snapped into place. She wanted to act like she didn't have a child, so I'd give her exactly what she asked for. I decided to lean into her declaration. If she wished she didn't have a child, then I'd honor that wish. I started simple. Changed my voicemail to a memorial message. You've reached the memorial line for Helen's daughter. Please leave condolences after the tone. Then I had funeral flowers delivered to her house, laying the foundation perfectly. Mom called me 37 times that day. I didn't answer. Next, I sent sympathy cards to all our relatives. Thinking of you during this difficult time of loss, they read. I signed them, a friend who cares. Whenever I ran into her church friends at the grocery store, I'd mention casually that I was planning a memorial service. Since mom declared she might as well not have a child, I figured I should honor her wishes, I'd say with a sad smile. It's what she wanted. Word spread fast through her social circles. People started asking mom about the service. She tried explaining I wasn't actually dead, but that made her look even worse. So you said you don't have a child, but you do? They'd ask. That's really messed up, Helen. The masterpiece came together when I scheduled my memorial for the same day as her charity club's Mother's Day luncheon. I rented the community center directly across the street from the country club, put up a big sign. Memorial service for Helen's child. I sent invitations to everyone. Helen recently declared she might as well not have a child at all. Please join us in acknowledging her loss. Light refreshments will be served. I included a screenshot of her Facebook post. The turnout was incredible. Turns out I wasn't the only one mom had hurt. Relatives poured in. Even cousin Sarah showed up. Meanwhile, mom's luncheon had maybe 12 ladies who kept glancing at my memorial through the windows. Every time someone left her event to check out mine, she got more frantic. She finally stormed into my memorial, face purple with rage. This is ridiculous. You're not dead. Stop this immediately. I stood calmly at the podium. I'm simply honoring what you posted, mom. You said you might as well not have a child. Mom left in tears, but not before snarling that I disappointed her one last time. The fallout was immediate, with her charity asking her to resign. Her Facebook posts were full of comments calling her the worst mother ever. Even her church friends stopped inviting her to get-togethers. And the best was that she couldn't play victim without explaining why her daughter was holding a memorial for herself. She trapped herself completely. Six months later, mom tells people I'm dramatic, but she stopped posting about disappointments and stopped comparing me to Sarah. She even sent a letter begging for reconciliation and asking me to tell people she was a good mother, but I just burned it.

Crazy things that happened at school. This person said that during their senior year of high school, someone took a massive dump in one of the girls' bathrooms. And by massive, I mean people said it was inhuman how large this poop was. Well, when the first kid saw this, they were amazed. Oh my god. Well, word spread pretty quickly, and within no time the entire school was made aware of this behemoth dump. And more than 50 students began skipping class to witness this incredible sight. Literally, they were lining up outside this bathroom, taking pictures with it. Oh my god, that's crazy. One kid was even genius enough to start charging admission to see the poop. Head on in. Hold on, you're next, don't worry. Five bucks? Guys, it's five bucks to see the poop. If you don't have it, please get out of the line. It's actually beautiful. I know. Mrs. Stevens? Shh, don't tell the principal. A plumber was then called and the poop was removed. People still talk about that day, the day someone's monster poop managed to bring a smile to the entire school.

People who sued a hospital and won, what's your story? In 2017, my mom got into a car accident. She lived three hours away and we tried our best to get to the hospital, but when we arrived, we learned she didn't make it. We found out that the hospital had already harvested her organs immediately after pronouncing her dead. My mom had never registered to be an organ donor, and without any agreement from us, they proceeded. In that same hospital, there was a 30-year-old woman on advanced life support who was at the top of the waiting list for a heart transplant. According to the hospital, someone had signed off claiming my mom was an organ donor. Our grief took a disturbing turn when the organ recipient contacted us to express gratitude. Out of curiosity, I decided to look into them. To my horror, I discovered that the recipient's husband was an EMT. Suspicion grew when I learned that he was the EMT who responded to my mom's accident. I went to the hospital and confirmed that the husband of the recipient was indeed the EMT who had rescued my mom. The court found him guilty after emotionally confessing trying to save his wife. He confirmed that my mom had a chance of survival if he had just tried harder. This made it even more difficult for us to accept knowing that my mom could have still been alive.

What's your "I did not see that one coming" story? For months, my son Toby had this stupid cough. He was nine years old, and it kept coming back every couple weeks. Not all the time, just when he ran around too much or played soccer. I took him to our doctor three different times. Each visit, same story. It's probably allergies, they said. Maybe post-nasal drip. They gave us some medicine, told him to take it easy, and sent us home. But it kept getting worse. One Saturday after soccer practice, Toby coughed so hard he almost passed out right there on the field. His face went white, and he grabbed onto my arm like he was drowning. I rushed him to urgent care immediately. They checked everything. His breathing, his heart, even did some blood tests. Nothing dangerous, they said. Just keep giving him the allergy meds. That night I was lying in bed thinking about it. Something felt off. The cough always seemed worse when we were at home, and it was only bad when we were upstairs. I started paying attention over the next few days. At school, no cough. When we stayed at my sister's house during the power outage last month, nothing. But upstairs in our house, especially in his bedroom, that's when it got really bad. So I did something that probably sounds crazy. I went online and bought one of those air quality monitors. You know, the kind that beeps if there's bad stuff in the air. When it arrived two days later, I plugged it in upstairs in Toby's room. Within ten minutes, this thing started screaming like a fire alarm. The screen was flashing red and showing these numbers I didn't understand, but I knew they were bad. I called the company's helpline. The guy on the phone got really quiet when I read him the numbers. Sir, you need to get your family out of that room immediately, he said. Those are toxic levels of formaldehyde. I didn't even know what that meant, but I moved Toby downstairs that same night. The next day, I started tearing his room apart. I pulled out his mattress, checked behind all the furniture, even looked under the carpet. Nothing made sense. The room looked normal. Then I remembered the built-in closet we had installed about two years ago. We hired this contractor I found online because he was way cheaper than everyone else. Big mistake. I got my tools and started ripping out the baseboard around the closet. That's when I found it. Behind the wood paneling was black mold so thick it looked like someone had painted the wall with tar. And underneath that was this old wooden beam that was completely rotted through. It was soaked with something that smelled like sewage mixed with glue. The whole thing was disgusting. I called a hazmat cleanup team that same day. They came out wearing those white suits like you see in the movies. After they finished cleaning everything out, Toby's cough disappeared completely. Just gone. I felt terrible that I hadn't figured it out sooner, but at least we solved it. But here's where it gets really weird. While I was packing up some of Toby's things from his room before the cleanup, I found this crumpled piece of paper stuck way down inside one of the loose floorboards. It was a letter written in purple ink by someone with really neat handwriting. The paper was old and yellowed around the edges. The letter was dated August 1997. It said, If anyone finds this, please tell my mom I didn't run away. I was trapped here. He kept me in the walls. He said I made too much noise coughing. It was signed, Samira. I stared at that letter for probably ten minutes, just trying to process what I was reading. My hands were shaking. I immediately called the police. They took the letter and started asking me all kinds of questions about the house and the previous owner. Two weeks later, a detective called me back. They had looked into it and found that Samira was a missing child case from 1997. She was 12 years old and had been living with a foster family. Her foster father was the main suspect, but they never had enough evidence to charge him. And get this, my house used to belong to him. The detective told me they were going to search the property with ground-penetrating radar. Three days later, they found her. She was buried in the crawlspace under the house, right below where Toby's room used to be. After 28 years, Samira's family finally got answers. The foster father had died five years ago, so there was never going to be a trial, but at least they could have closure. Her mom sent me a letter thanking me for finding Samira's note and giving her daughter peace.

Gave my ex a surprise when I left unexpectedly. Three months ago, I was living with my ex-girlfriend Ashley and we were splitting a one-bedroom apartment. She worked at some boutique downtown making like $12 an hour, but acted like she was running her own fashion empire. I was doing night shifts at a warehouse making decent money, but she always complained I was never home enough or that I smelled like cardboard when I got back. The thing is, Ashley had this weird habit of going through my stuff when she thought I wasn't paying attention. She'd check my phone when I was in the shower, go through my wallet while I was sleeping, and even rearrange my dresser drawers claiming she was just helping me stay organized. I caught her doing it multiple times, but every time I brought it up she'd flip it around and say I was being paranoid or controlling. What really got to me was when she started opening my mail. Not just bills or whatever, but personal stuff too. She opened a birthday card from my grandma with 50 bucks in it, and when I asked her about it she said the envelope was already torn and she was just trying to help. The money was sitting right there on the counter so I couldn't prove she took any, but something felt off. Then last month I ordered this vintage baseball card I'd been wanting since I was a kid. Cost me like 200 bucks but it was mint condition and from my favorite player. The package showed up while I was at work, and when I got home Ashley was acting all weird and nervous. When I asked about packages, she said nothing came, but I had the tracking info showing it was delivered. I went to our apartment manager's office the next day and asked to see the security footage from our hallway. Sure enough, there was Ashley taking my package inside. When I confronted her she broke down crying saying she sold it on eBay because she needed money for some emergency. Turned out the emergency was a pair of boots she saw online. That's when I decided I was done, but I wasn't just going to pack up and leave like a normal person. Ashley had this thing where she kept a journal under her mattress that she wrote in every single night. She thought I didn't know about it but I'd seen her writing in it plenty of times. She'd always cover it up real quick if I walked by and hide it immediately after. So I came up with my plan. I waited until she went to work one Saturday morning and I knew she'd be gone for 8 hours. I carefully lifted up her side of the mattress and found the journal. Instead of reading it, I left it exactly where it was, but I put a tiny piece of tape on the cover that would break if anyone opened it. Then I packed up all my stuff while leaving everything that looked like mine still in place. I took my clothes but left empty hangers. Took my gaming console but left the controllers plugged into nothing. Moved out my dresser but left the drawer handles on the floor where it used to be. I even took my half of the shower curtain so there was just this weird gap in the bathroom. But here's the best part. I wrote her a note and put it inside her journal right on the page she'd probably write on next. The note said, Hey Ashley, since you love going through my stuff so much, I figured you wouldn't mind if I went through yours. Don't worry, I only read the parts where you wrote about cheating on me with Brad from your work. Hope you two are happy together. By the way, I'm keeping the security deposit since you owe me 200 bucks for my baseball card. Have fun explaining to the landlord why half the apartment is missing. The thing is, I never actually read her journal, but I knew she was paranoid enough to think I did, and I was pretty sure she was cheating based on how she'd been acting lately. It was basically a shot in the dark, but I figured if I was wrong, she'd just be confused, and if I was right, she'd probably freak out. I left that Saturday afternoon and drove to my buddy's place where I'd already arranged to crash on his couch. Around 11 that night, my phone started blowing up with texts and calls from Ashley. First she was confused, then angry, then crying, then angry again. The messages went from where are you to what did you do to my apartment to how dare you read my journal to please come back, we can work this out. But the one that confirmed everything was when she texted, I can explain about Brad, it's not what you think. So I was right about the cheating. I never responded to any of her messages and I blocked her number the next day.

I kept my name change a secret for five years. My parents had a strange sense of humor when naming their kids. My brother got the name Everest, which he loved, strong, unique, and meaningful. Me? They named me Minnesota. They thought it was quirky and charming, but for me, it was a nightmare. In school, I was teased mercilessly. Kids called me Mini-Soda or just Soda Can. My parents insisted that everyone use my full name, saying it was a badge of honor. Even teachers winced when calling roll. By the time I turned 18, I was done. I legally changed my name to Nina and didn't tell a soul. College was a fresh start. Everyone knew me as Nina, and for the first time, I felt normal. My boyfriend Aaron even said my name sounded elegant. I didn't have the heart or courage to tell him the truth. Fast forward five years, Aaron proposed, and I said yes. Everything was perfect until I realized my birth name would be announced during the wedding ceremony. I had no choice but to tell my parents and Aaron the truth. When I told my parents, they were furious. They called me ungrateful, saying I destroyed a piece of our family's legacy. Aaron's reaction? He just stared at me, speechless. Finally, he said, why didn't you trust me with this? The wedding's next week, and my parents refuse to come. Aaron says he needs time to think. My brother Everest, though, texted me last night. I wish I'd changed my name too. You're braver than I'll ever be. I don't regret becoming Nina, but standing at the altar next week, I wonder, will I be standing there?

What's the worst thing a neighbor did that you will never forgive them for? I've lived in this house for 25 years, raised my kids here, and it's been my only home since I left my parents. In 2009, tragedy struck when my daughter was right in front of our home by a drunk teen driver. She was out in our front garden, a place she loved, when he came barreling down the road and hit her. She didn't even have time to react. That driver turned out to be our neighbor's son. After she passed, I laid her urn to rest in the garden, the very place she loved most, and planted her favorite hydrangeas right where she last stood. Those flowers were a memorial to her. It took five long years for them to bloom. It was a bittersweet moment, seeing those flowers she loved so much finally blossom. But just five days later, I caught that same neighbor cutting down the hydrangeas and taking the entire bush. I was devastated and confronted her, asking why she would do such a thing. Her excuse? She said her daughter needed flowers for her wedding, and that's the least I can do for getting her son sent to jail and ruining his life. I had to remind her that her son took my daughter's life, and those flowers were a tribute. The other neighbors found out and made her life miserable, every single day, until she couldn't take it anymore and moved out.

Parents of killers, what's your story? I have one son and three daughters. My son, being the eldest, has always been protective of his sisters. So when I found out what he had done, I wasn't entirely surprised. My 13-year-old daughter complained of feeling unwell and had severe stomach pain. Initially, I thought it was just the flu, but then it got worse. While I was at work, he took her to the emergency room, where they waited for hours, only to discover that my daughter was pregnant. She cried and apologized, explaining that her gymnastics coach had threatened to remove her from the team if she didn't comply with him. Out of fear, she had been forced to endure unimaginable pain. After hearing this, my son left. The next day, we learned that the coach had passed away. Someone had broken into his home at midnight. The news spread quickly, and numerous past and current students came forward to testify. The case was so disturbing that authorities didn't bother to investigate or pursue the killer. Fearing of being caught, my son never returned home. Despite our pleas for him to come home and the fact that the case had been closed, the only response he gave was that he had failed as a brother and couldn't forgive himself for not protecting his sister. To me and our family, he will always be a hero. This all happened more than 30 years ago.

If you ever hear this sound, don't do what she did. Sally loved dancing, she danced anytime she got the chance. She especially loved dancing around the garden while her mother worked. She enjoyed the sounds the crickets made. Her mother noticed she seemed distracted lately. Her dancing had started getting bad and so had her balance. Her mother took her to the doctors. They did some tests. When they saw what the cause was they were horrified. A cricket had crawled into Sally's ear and had eaten into her brain. What was worse is it had laid eggs and they had begun to hatch.

I had an old neighbor who was rumored to be dangerous. Growing up, there were all sorts of stories about him circulating in the neighborhood. People said he was crazy and that he had a wife secretly. Our parents used to warn us about him. But one year my brothers and I decided to knock on his door for trick-or-treating. We were terrified, but we knocked. And to our surprise, he opened the door with the biggest smile. We peeked inside and saw that his house was well-kept. He greeted us warmly and said, you guys made my day. I always buy chocolates every year, but no kid ever comes by. He filled our bags with tons of chocolates. It honestly made me sad that he was just a simple, harmless old man. We didn't tell our parents, but since then, we would visit him to say hi. He was always excited to see us. He has been alone for 30 years after his wife passed away from giving birth. We visited him regularly until we left for college. When he passed away, my brothers and I went back home for his funeral. To our surprise, after the sale of his home, the proceeds were given to us. The lawyer handed us a letter from him, which said, your presence gave me hope and you are the first ones I will tell my wife about.

Remix lets you use the sound or visuals from other shorts. Here's how to do it. When you come across a short you want to remix, tap this icon. You can choose from sound, collab, green screen, or cut. Sound lets you use the same audio or song from the short you're remixing. You can adjust how much of the sound you want to use by tapping it. Collab lets you create side by side with the short you're remixing. Drag the edges of the clip to adjust what part of the short you want to collab with. Then, tap next to choose your collab layout and record your short. Green screen lets you use the short you are remixing as your background. Adjust which part of the short you want to use as your background, then tap done to begin recording your short. Cut lets you use a part of the short in the beginning of your short. Adjust the clip length, then tap done. The clip you selected will then be added to the beginning of your new short. What will you create with remix? Try it out!

What's something your parents did that backfired badly? I was born with blonde hair, just like my parents. But by the time I was three or four, it started to darken. My mom freaked out. From then on, she started secretly dyeing my hair. Who knows what kind of chemicals she used. Every few weeks, whenever my dad wasn't around, she'd do it. One day, she half-jokingly admitted she didn't want him to think I wasn't his because my hair had changed. She made it clear that if our hair didn't stay blonde, dad would get upset. She kept up the routine until I was 15. And it wasn't just me. She did the same to my siblings. Anyone born with blonde hair was dyed to keep it that way. We all suffered from burns and allergies from the chemicals. But she was determined to keep up the lie. Then, 25 years later, the truth came out. It all started with a medical scare that required a detailed family history. A DNA test revealed the bombshell. None of us were actually my dad's kids. The reason my mom obsessed over our hair color was to hide her affairs. She'd had five of them with five different men. My dad was crushed by the betrayal, and he ended up divorcing her and suing for damages.

What's the wildest thing you've seen a parent allow? I witnessed something at my local library that changed how I see the world. It was a rainy Tuesday afternoon, when I went to return some books. The children's section was busier than usual because of the weather, with kids sprawled on colorful beanbags while parents chatted nearby. That's when I noticed them. A thin boy about eight years old with a stack of books beside him, and his dad sitting across from him. Nothing strange at first, until I realized the boy hadn't turned a page in over twenty minutes. He was just staring at the same page, his finger tracing the words over and over. The dad would occasionally lean over, point to a word, and wait. The boy would struggle, his face scrunching up with effort, then... whisper something. His dad would either nod or gently shake his head. I found a seat nearby and pretended to read while watching this painfully slow process. Other kids zipped through colorful picture books while this boy fought for every single word. After an hour, they only made it through six pages. The librarian walked by and smiled warmly at him. Back again, you two? Fourth day this week. That's when I noticed the boy's clothes, the same faded blue shirt he'd worn yesterday when I'd been here. His sneakers had holes near the toes. When the library announced closing time, the dad carefully marked their place with a receipt and closed the book. The boy looked devastated. But dad, we didn't finish Harry's adventure today. His dad knelt down. We'll pick up tomorrow where we left off, buddy. Promise. The boy looked at the book longingly. I wish we could take it home. I know, his dad said quietly. As they walked toward the exit, I overheard the librarian ask, Still no luck with the job search? The dad shook his head. Three interviews this week, but nothing yet. We're okay, though. The next day, I arrived early with a plan. I spotted them in the same corner and approached cautiously. Excuse me, I said. I work with a children's literacy program. We're giving away book club memberships and your son was recommended by the staff here. The dad looked surprised. Really? I nodded, trying to sound official. It includes a library card with all fees covered for a year and one book to keep each month. The boy's eyes widened. My own books? To keep forever? That's right, I said, pulling out a gift card I'd bought that morning. This covers everything. You just need to sign this form. I handed over a made-up application. The dad studied it carefully. I could see the pride fighting with necessity in his eyes. This is very generous, but... Dad, please, the boy whispered. I could practice at home, too. Something in his father's expression broke. He signed the paper and handed it back to me. For three weeks, I saw them every afternoon. The boy carefully chose a new book each week, and his reading improved noticeably. His dad found occasional day labor that paid cash. Things seemed to be looking up. Then one day, they didn't show up. Or the next day. Or the day after that. A week later, I found the librarian sorting books. Have you seen the man with his son? The ones who come in to read every day? Her face fell. You didn't hear? There was a fire in their building last night. One of those old apartment complexes without proper alarms. My heart stopped. Are they okay? She shook her head. The dad didn't make it out. They said he went back in for something. The boy's in the hospital with smoke inhalation. But he'll survive. I felt sick. What will happen to him? No other family that we know of. Child services is involved. The next morning, I went to the hospital. I didn't know the boy's full name, so I just described him to the nurses. One recognized him and reluctantly let me visit for five minutes. He was small in the hospital bed, oxygen tubes in his nose. On the table beside him was a charred, water-damaged copy of Harry Potter, the book they'd been reading together. Your dad went back for the book, I whispered, understanding hitting me like a punch. The boy nodded, his eyes hollow. He promised we'd finish it. His voice was raspy from the smoke. I sat with him, my heart breaking as he opened the damaged book. Most pages were ruined, but he turned to page 189, exactly where they'd left off that last day at the library. I started reading where his father would never get to. The boy closed his eyes, tears streaming down his face. Two days later, they transferred him to a group home. I tried to visit, but they wouldn't let me in. Family only, they said. I left my number with the staff. Please, just give him this message. I'll keep the book safe until he can finish it. A month passed, then two. I visited the group home weekly, but they always turned me away. One cold morning, I found a small package at my door. Inside was the burned copy of Harry Potter and a note from a social worker. He wanted you to have this. He said his dad would want someone to finish it. He's being moved to a foster home in another state tomorrow. I never saw the boy again, but every year on the anniversary of the fire, I read one chapter of that burned book out loud. I'm not religious, but I like to think his dad can hear it somehow. That one day, the story will be finished. Some promises survive even when people can't.

Parents, when did you know you raised your child right? When my 14-year-old daughter, Lily, asked if she could go to the mall with her friends. Nothing unusual, just teenagers being teenagers. I handed her some cash, reminded her not to stay out too late, and went back to folding laundry, thinking nothing of it. A few hours later, my phone rang. Unknown number. Hello? This is Officer Daniels from the city police. Your daughter is at the station. You should come right away. My stomach dropped. Is she hurt? What happened? I'll explain when you get here, ma'am. That drive felt endless. My mind raced with every possible worst-case scenario. When I arrived, I spotted Lily in a chair, pale but oddly calm. She gave me a small, tight smile, the kind that said, I'm fine, but I'm not sure you'll think so. The officer began, Your daughter stopped a theft at the mall. She followed the suspect into the parking garage. That could have gone very wrong. I turned to her, stunned. You did what? She explained she'd been in a small jewelry store when she noticed a man slipping a diamond necklace into his jacket. No one else seemed to notice. She froze for a moment, debating whether to say something, but when he walked out casually, she followed at a distance, texting the store owner about what she'd seen. The man descended into the dim parking garage. Lily noticed a young woman leaning over a stroller, The man kept glancing around, as if deciding his next move.
